Varroosis of honey bees, Mauritius
----------------------------------
Information received on [and dated] 3 Dec 2014 from Dr Deodass Meenowa, Principal Agricultural Officer(Veterinary Services), Division of Veterinary Services, Ministry of Agro-Industry and Food Security, Reduit, Mauritius

Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Date of start of the event: 12 Aug 2014
Date of pre-confirmation of the event: 12 Aug 2014
Report date: 3 Dec 2014
Date submitted to OIE: 3 Dec 2014
Reason for notification: 1st occurrence of a listed disease
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: _Varroa destructor_
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, laboratory (basic), laboratory
This event pertains to whole country

New outbreaks (1)
Summary of outbreaks
Total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak 1: Pointe aux Sables, Black River, Mauritius
Date of start of the outbreak: 12 Aug 2014
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: apiary
Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Bees (hives) / 3000 / 88 / 88 / 52 / 0

Outbreak statistics [rates apparent, expressed as percentages]
Species / Morbidity rate / Mortality rate / Case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Bees (hives) / 2.93 / 2.93 / 100 / 4.67
*Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction, and/or slaughter

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: introduction of new live animals; illegal movement of animals

Epidemiological comments: This is the 1st record of this quarantine pest in honey bees in Mauritius. The adults observed show deformed wings. It is regarded as an external parasite that reproduces in honey bee colonies. Infestation eventually leads to death of colonies. 353 bee colonies found in the buffer zone have been treated with mite control products as of 9 Sep 2014. Treatment of bee colonies in the buffer zone and elimination of all bee colonies in the affected regions are being pursued.

Control measures
Measures applied: stamping out; quarantine; movement control inside the country; screening; zoning; disinfection of infected premises/establishment(s); dipping/spraying; no vaccination; treatment of affected animals (tau-fluvalinate and thymol gel)

Measures to be applied: no other measures

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
Entomology Laboratory, Reduit (national laboratory) / bees / parasitological examination / 12 Aug 2014 / Positive

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.

