[Varroa mites are parasites of adult bees and their brood. Four species have been recorded: _Varroa jacobsoni_, _V. destructor_, _V. underwoodi_ and _V. rinderi_. Until recently, varroa mites that affect _Apis mellifera_ worldwide were assumed to be _V. jacobsoni_. However it has been shown that these mites are _V. destructor_.

They are responsible for the condition of varroosis or varroatosis. The mite inserts itself between the abdominal sclera in adult bees where it penetrates the intersegmental membranes in order to ingest haemolymph. Sometimes it can also be found between the head and thorax. For reproduction, the female enters the cells with the bee brood shortly before the cells are sealed.

The course of this parasitism is usually lethal, except in some areas, such as tropical Latin America. The life span of mites on larval or adult bees depends on temperature and humidity. Under practical conditions, the life span may vary from days to a few months. In heavily infested bee colonies, clinical signs of varroosis can often 1st be seen in the latter part of the season when the brood is reduced. Heavy infestations are usually reached 3-4 years after the primary invasion, but can occur within weeks if infested by bees from nearby colonies that are collapsing.

For the above and additional background information including diagnostic methods and references, please refer to the OIE Terrestrial Manual 2014, Chapter 2.2.7 "Varroosis of honey bees" at http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Health_standards/tahm/2.02.07_VARROOSIS.pdf.

Pictures of _Varroa destructor_ can be seen at http://entnemdept.ufl.edu/creatures/misc/bees/varroa_mite.htm.

According to a recent OIE press release on bee issues, the OIE launched a new OIE thematic publication entitled "Bee health and veterinarians:"

"Preserving the health of bees, both in the wild and in apiaries, is now a crucial health issue and one that the OIE includes among its priorities. Any loss of these key pollinators, which help to ensure plentiful crops throughout the world, would be a biological, agricultural, environmental and economic disaster.

"Increasing bee mortality is a growing concern worldwide. It has multiple causes, including factors such as environmental influences, irresponsible use of pesticides, emergence of new pathogens and harmful practices in world trade in bees and bee products.

"Public and private sector veterinarians have a growing role to play in protecting the health of bees, whatever the reasons for their deteriorating health status. Veterinarians, along with the other stakeholders in the beekeeping sector, are responsible for supporting and helping to implement measures and activities aimed at improving bee health. This new OIE publication provides the key to understanding the distribution of responsibilities within the beekeeping sector and gives veterinarians and all the other stakeholders in the sector an update on essential information for the prevention and control of bee diseases."

See http://www.oie.int/en/for-the-media/press-releases/detail/article/veterinarians-key-players-in-preserving-bee-health/.

For more information, subscribers may be interested in reading the following articles available on-line:
- Editorial: "Protecting bees to safeguard our future," http://www.oie.int/en/for-the-media/editorials/detail/article/protecting-bees-to-safeguard-our-future/, Dr Bernard Vallat, Director General of the OIE.
- General introductory text providing background information for the chapters of the Terrestrial Animal Health Code on diseases of bees, http://www.oie.int/en/our-scientific-expertise/specific-information-and-recommendations/bee-diseases/.
- OIE Bulletin, 2014(2): Protecting bees, preserving our future, http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Publications_%26_Documentation/docs/pdf/bulletin/Bull_2014-2-ENG.pdf..

